## The SAR Is Not the Finish Line

Day 61 produced the Security Assessment Report — seven findings, three Moderate and four Low, with an assessor recommendation of conditional authorization pending remediation of the three Moderate findings within defined timelines. Today, Task A-5 begins: the system owner receives the SAR findings and takes action.

Task A-5 is specifically about remediation actions taken *before* the authorization package is submitted to the AO. Not all findings need to be remediated before authorization — that is what the POA&M handles for findings that will be addressed post-authorization. But the SAR gave a clear recommendation: remediate the three Moderate findings, particularly Finding A-3 (the undocumented service account with console access and no MFA), within specific timelines. The question for Task A-5 is: what can we fix right now, before the authorization package goes to the AO, to strengthen the authorization package and reduce the conditions the AO needs to impose?

The answer to that question requires honest triage — not panic-remediating everything, which would delay authorization unnecessarily, and not deferring everything to the POA&M, which would undermine the credibility of the authorization package. Task A-5 is disciplined, evidence-backed remediation of the highest-priority items.

