## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

Working through the IAM PassRole remediation today — specifically the process of determining which roles the IT Administrator legitimately needs to be able to pass — reminded me of the circumstances surrounding the **2019 CapitalOne breach** in a way I had not fully appreciated before.

The Paige Thompson attack began with a Server Side Request Forgery vulnerability that allowed retrieval of IAM credentials from the EC2 metadata service. Those credentials belonged to a WAF role that had been granted `s3:GetObject` and `s3:ListBucket` permissions far broader than the WAF role needed for its operational function. The WAF needed to write logs to one specific S3 bucket — it did not need read access to the 700+ S3 buckets it ended up being able to access.

The remediation discipline for Finding A-1 follows the same principle — identify exactly what the IT Administrator legitimately needs PassRole to accomplish (pass two named roles), and restrict the permission to exactly that scope. The before state (wildcard resource) was operationally convenient — it would never break anything. The after state (two named roles) is operationally equivalent for legitimate use cases but eliminates the entire class of privilege escalation scenarios that the wildcard resource permitted.

The CapitalOne parallel makes clear that "it probably won't be abused" is not sufficient justification for a wildcard permission in a High-impact system. The permission scope should match the operational requirement, and the operational requirement should be verified — not assumed.

