## What I Am Still Thinking About

The Finding A-4 deferral — modification audit logs not capturing previous values — requires a decision between implementing previous value logging and updating the SSP to accept current logging capability as HIPAA-sufficient. I deferred this to the POA&M to allow deliberate decision-making, but I want to think through which option is actually the right answer for MyClinic.

The case for implementing previous value logging: it is the technically complete solution. It would make the SSP accurate. It would provide better investigation capability if a data integrity incident occurred — knowing what a record said before it was modified is genuinely useful for determining whether a change was authorized.

The case for accepting current logging with a documented rationale: HIPAA's audit control standard does not require previous value capture. The current logging provides full access accountability. Healthcare organizations operating on constrained IT resources have a legitimate interest in not gold-plating audit logging beyond regulatory requirements when those resources could address the open CP-2 and IR-3 gaps that have more direct patient safety implications.

My instinct is that for MyClinic — a small clinic with limited IT resources — the right answer is the documented risk acceptance option. Implement previous value logging if OpenMRS makes it operationally straightforward; if it requires custom development, document the HIPAA sufficiency rationale and accept the gap explicitly. The Compliance Officer's interview demonstrated that the organization understands its HIPAA obligations — this is a decision they can make deliberately, not a gap they are unaware of.

